<div class="quotetitle">getafixx wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />is that 32mbit cart unfinished? You seem to be missing your '257s.<br /></div><br /><br />Not, not missing them. When mounting a 16Mbit game, you can avoid mounting both multiplexers if you re-arrange the data in the EPROM so the data outputs from D0 to D7 only. The data is shifted and A20 becomes A0, thus the floating wire you can see in the board.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">benjaminsantiago wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />These look great, I like the ad for buyicnow.com <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /></div><br /><br />It's not an ad XDD They programmed the chips and they put the label in the EPROM to make clear what is burned in each one. They shipped the EPROMs the way you see.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">benjaminsantiago wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />What is going on with those discrete components under the batteries?<br /></div><br /><br />It's the SRAM-standby trigger circuit: it drives /CE and VCC_SRAM to keep the data in the SRAM when powering-off the SNES.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=875">magno</a> — Fri Feb 21, 2014 1:57 am</p><hr />
